04543nam a22006015i 9781438464169DE-B159720240307104700.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240307t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a9781438464169  a(DE-B1597)681770  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a330.12/2qOCoLC223/eng/20230216  aCC 7750qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17690:1 aStimilli, Elettra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Debt of the Living :bAscesis and Capitalism /cElettra Stimilli. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (216 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 0  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSUNY series in Contemporary Italian Philosophy00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tForeword to the English Translation -- tPreface to the English Translation -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe End in Itself of the Economic Enterprise -- tOikonomía and Asceticism -- tThe Theological Construction of the Government of the World -- tVoluntary Poverty on the Market -- tCapitalism as Religion -- tA Philosophical Critique of Asceticism -- tThe Spirit of Capitalism and Forms of Life -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMax Weber's account of the rise of capitalism focused on his concept of a Protestant ethic, valuing diligence in earning and saving money but restraint in spending it. However, such individual restraint is foreign to contemporary understandings of finance, which treat ever-increasing consumption and debt as natural, almost essential, for maintaining the economic cycle of buying and selling.In The Debt of the Living, Elettra Stimilli returns to this idea of restraint as ascesis, by analyzing theological and philosophical understandings of debt drawn from a range of figures, including Saint Paul, Schmitt and Agamben, Benjamin and Marx, Nietzsche and Freud, and Foucault. Central to this analysis is the logic of "profit for profit's sake"—an aspect of Weber's work that Stimilli believes has been given insufficient attention. Following Foucault, she identifies this as the original mechanism of a capitalist dispositif that feeds not on a goal-directed rationality, but on the self-determining character of human agency. Ascesis is fundamental not because it is characterized by renunciation, but because the self-discipline it imposes converts the properly human quality of action without a predetermined goal into a lack, a fault, or a state of guilt: a debt that cannot be settled. Stimilli argues that this lack, which is impossible to fill, should be seen as the basis of the economy of hedonism and consumption that has governed global economies in recent years and as the premise of the current economy of debt.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aAsceticism. 0aCapitalismxReligious aspects. 0aCapitalism. 0aReligion and sociology. 4aBusiness and Economics : Economy and Society. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theology. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aBove, Arianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsposito, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStimilli, Elettra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2016z978311149098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438464169423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438464169/original  a978-3-11-149098-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles